            <div class="media-body">
              <h4 class="media-heading">Description</h4>
              This project is an open source release of tools for cardiovascular simulation. It includes software for loading and viewing medical image data, segmenting vascular anatomy, generating 3D patient specific models and meshes, and modeling blood flow in deformable vessels. The SimVascular originated in the lab of Charles Taylor at Stanford University, and is now maintained by an active community of domestic and international academic and industrial researchers. The project is part of the Stanford Simbios Center hosted on simtk.org. The SimVascular revitalization project, started in 2013 by Alison Marsden, Shawn Shadden and Nathan Wilson, aims to provide the first truly open source package for cardiovascular simulation with enhanced funcationality for both clinical and basic science research.
            </div>
          </div>
          <!-- Purpose/Synopsis -->
          <div class="media">
            <a class="pull-left" href="#">
              <img class="media-object" src="img/Img_About_Femoral.png" alt="...">
            </a>
            <div class="media-body">
              <h4 class="media-heading">Purpose</h4>
              Provides a platform for patient-specific cardiovascular modeling and simulation to support research and clinical efforts in medical computing. SimVascular represents the state of the art in the CV simulation community, including advanced tools for physiologic boundary conditions, fluid structure interaction (FSI), and an accurate and efficient finite element flow solver.
            </div>
          </div>
          <!-- Audience -->
          <div class="media">
            <a class="pull-left" href="#">
